Mohamed Abdullahi Mohamed (File: AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories New York - Somalia's president Mohamed Abdullahi Mohamed is urging the world to help avert a massive famine saying almost half the population is facing acute food shortages and 15% are facing famine now.Mohamed told the UN Security Council by videolink from Mogadishu on Thursday that Somalis are resilient and would be the last to ask for help but drought has spawned a humanitarian crisis that could threaten the country's political and security gains.The United Nations said on Wednesday that the $864m UN humanitarian appeal for Somalia is only 31% funded.British Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson visited Somalia last week and presided over the meeting. He said the country is facing its third famine in 25 years and over 6 million people - about half the population - need help.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.